<DOC><DOCNO> AP890117-0184 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2049EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     01-17 0235</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Salvador,0240</SECOND><HEAD>Guerrillas Attack In Northern Province</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leftist guerrillas Tuesdaylaunched coordinated attacks on military positions in six northerntowns, the armed forces and the rebels reported.   The armed forces said three rebels were killed and three soldierswounded in the battles before dawn in the northern province ofChalatenango. The guerrillas said they caused 25 casualties amongarmy troops, but did not specify the number of dead and wounded.   The rebels, who commented on the clandestine Radio FarbundoMarti, did not mention their own losses. The radio, like theMarxist-led Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front that has beenbattling the U.S.-backed government for nine years, is named for a1930s revolutionary.   The armed forces press office, as well as the clandestineguerrilla radio, reported fighting in and around the towns of DulceNombre de Maria, El Refugio, La Laguna, San Ignacio and San Miguelde Mercedes. The rebels also staged what the army called``harassment'' attacks on positions around the 4th Infantry Brigadeheadquarters at El Paraiso, 28 miles north of San Salvador, thecapital.   The insurgents said the coordinated attacks were part of anoperation called ``In response to repression, the people andmilitias prepare the insurrection.''   Rebel forces also blew up three utility posts near Apopa, sevenmiles north of the capital, causing temporary blackouts in thecapital and some northern sectors of the country.</TEXT></DOC>